              <h2>How this payback period calculator works</h2>
              <p>
                This tool evaluates an investment by projecting its cash flows
                over time and computing:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Simple payback period</strong> (undiscounted cash
                  flows)
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Discounted payback period</strong> (time value of
                  money included)
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Net present value (NPV)</strong> at the chosen
                  discount rate
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Profitability index (PI)</strong>, i.e. NPV per dollar
                  invested
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>1. Simple payback period formula</h3>
              <p>
                The simple payback period is the time it takes for cumulative
                cash flows to recover the initial investment. For irregular cash
                flows, we use cumulative sums and linear interpolation.
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p><strong>Step 1 – Cumulative cash flow</strong></p>
                <p>
                  Let \( I_0 \) be the initial investment (negative cash flow)
                  and \( CF_t \) the net cash flow in year \( t \).
                </p>
                <p>Cumulative cash flow after year \( n \):</p>
                <p>\[ CCF_n = -I_0 + \sum_{t=1}^{n} CF_t \]</p>
                <p><strong>Step 2 – Find the year of recovery</strong></p>
                <p>
                  Find the first year \( k \) such that \( CCF_k \ge 0 \). If
                  payback occurs between years \( k-1 \) and \( k \):
                </p>
                <p>\[ \text{Payback} = (k-1) + \frac{|CCF_{k-1}|}{CF_k} \]</p>
              </div>

              <h3>2. Discounted payback period formula</h3>
              <p>
                The discounted payback period uses discounted cash flows, so
                that money received later is worth less today.
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>
                  <strong>Present value of cash flow in year \( t \)</strong> at
                  discount rate \( r \):
                </p>
                <p>\[ DCF_t = \frac{CF_t}{(1 + r)^t} \]</p>
                <p>Cumulative discounted cash flow after year \( n \):</p>
                <p>\[ CDCF_n = -I_0 + \sum_{t=1}^{n} DCF_t \]</p>
                <p>
                  As with simple payback, find the first year \( k \) where \(
                  CDCF_k \ge 0 \), then interpolate:
                </p>
                <p>
                  \[ \text{Discounted payback} = (k-1) +
                  \frac{|CDCF_{k-1}|}{DCF_k} \]
                </p>
              </div>

              <h3>3. Net present value (NPV) and profitability index (PI)</h3>
              <p>
                While payback focuses on how quickly you recover your
                investment, NPV and PI measure overall value creation.
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p><strong>Net present value (NPV)</strong></p>
                <p>\[ NPV = -I_0 + \sum_{t=1}^{N} \frac{CF_t}{(1 + r)^t} \]</p>
                <p><strong>Profitability index (PI)</strong></p>
                <p>
                  \[ PI = \frac{\text{Present value of future cash
                  inflows}}{I_0} = \frac{\sum_{t=1}^{N} \frac{CF_t}{(1 +
                  r)^t}}{I_0} \]
                </p>
              </div>

              <h2>How to use the payback period calculator</h2>
              <ol>
                <li>
                  <strong>Enter the initial investment</strong> as a positive
                  amount (e.g. 100,000). The calculator treats it as an outflow
                  at year 0.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Set the discount rate</strong> (optional but
                  recommended). Use your cost of capital or required rate of
                  return.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Fill in the yearly cash flows</strong> as net amounts
                  (inflows minus outflows) for each year.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Click “Calculate payback period”</strong> to see
                  simple and discounted payback, NPV, PI, and the full cash flow
                  table.
                </li>
              </ol>

              <h3>Interpreting the results</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Simple payback</strong>: quick, intuitive measure of
                  risk and liquidity, but ignores the time value of money and
                  cash flows after payback.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Discounted payback</strong>: more rigorous, but still
                  ignores cash flows after the cutoff date.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>NPV</strong>: best single measure of value creation; a
                  positive NPV means the project adds value at the chosen
                  discount rate.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>PI</strong>: useful for ranking projects when capital
                  is limited; PI &gt; 1 indicates value creation.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>FAQ</h2>

              <h3>What is a good payback period?</h3>
              <p>
                It depends on your industry, risk tolerance, and capital
                constraints. Many companies set an internal
                <em>maximum acceptable payback period</em> (for example 3–5
                years). Projects with a payback shorter than this threshold are
                considered, while longer projects may be rejected or require
                stronger strategic justification.
              </p>

              <h3>Why can payback period be misleading?</h3>
              <p>Payback period:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Ignores cash flows after the payback date (two projects with
                  the same payback can have very different NPVs).
                </li>
                <li>
                  Does not directly measure profitability or shareholder value.
                </li>
                <li>In its simple form, ignores the time value of money.</li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                For this reason, it is best used as a
                <strong>screening tool</strong> alongside NPV, IRR, and
                qualitative factors.
              </p>

              <h3>Should I use simple or discounted payback?</h3>
              <p>
                If you want a quick, rough sense of how fast you recover your
                cash, simple payback is fine. If you are comparing projects with
                different risk profiles or long horizons,
                <strong>discounted payback</strong> is more appropriate because
                it accounts for the time value of money.
              </p>

              <h3>Can payback period be negative or not exist?</h3>
              <p>
                The payback period is defined only if cumulative (simple or
                discounted) cash flows eventually become zero or positive. If
                the project never recovers the initial investment, the
                calculator will show that
                <strong
                  >no payback is achieved within the entered horizon</strong
                >.
