<section class="bg-white p-4 rounded-lg shadow-md mt-6"><h2 class="text-lg font-semibold mb-2">Inputs used by this calculator</h2><ul class="text-sm text-gray-700 list-disc pl-5"><li>Initial investment $ Enter as a positive number (the tool will treat it as an outflow). Discount rate (for discounted payback) % Use your cost of capital or required return. Leave 0 to ignore discounted payback. Cash flows by year + Add year Enter net cash flow for each year (inflows minus outflows). You can add or remove years as needed. Calculate payback period Reset Please enter a positive initial investment and at least one non-zero cash flow. Results Simple payback period – Waiting for input… Discounted payback period – Requires a positive discount rate. Total undiscounted cash flow – Net present value (NPV) – Profitability index (PI) – Cash flow timeline Year Cash flow Cumulative CF Discounted CF Cum. discounted CF Recovery? How this payback period calculator works This tool evaluates an investment by projecting its cash flows over time and computing: Simple payback period (undiscounted cash flows) Discounted payback period (time value of money included) Net present value (NPV) at the chosen discount rate Profitability index (PI) , i.e. NPV per dollar invested 1. Simple payback period formula The simple payback period is the time it takes for cumulative cash flows to recover the initial investment. For irregular cash flows, we use cumulative sums and linear interpolation. Step 1 – Cumulative cash flow Let \( I_0 \) be the initial investment (negative cash flow) and \( CF_t \) the net cash flow in year \( t \). Cumulative cash flow after year \( n \): \[ CCF_n = -I_0 + \sum_{t=1}^{n} CF_t \] Step 2 – Find the year of recovery Find the first year \( k \) such that \( CCF_k \ge 0 \). If payback occurs between years \( k-1 \) and \( k \): \[ \text{Payback} = (k-1) + \frac{|CCF_{k-1}|}{CF_k} \] 2. Discounted payback period formula The discounted payback period uses discounted cash flows, so that money received later is worth less today. Present value of cash flow in year \( t \) at discount rate \( r \): \[ DCF_t = \frac{CF_t}{(1 + r)^t} \] Cumulative discounted cash flow after year \( n \): \[ CDCF_n = -I_0 + \sum_{t=1}^{n} DCF_t \] As with simple payback, find the first year \( k \) where \( CDCF_k \ge 0 \), then interpolate: \[ \text{Discounted payback} = (k-1) + \frac{|CDCF_{k-1}|}{DCF_k} \] 3. Net present value (NPV) and profitability index (PI) While payback focuses on how quickly you recover your investment, NPV and PI measure overall value creation. Net present value (NPV) \[ NPV = -I_0 + \sum_{t=1}^{N} \frac{CF_t}{(1 + r)^t} \] Profitability index (PI) \[ PI = \frac{\text{Present value of future cash inflows}}{I_0} = \frac{\sum_{t=1}^{N} \frac{CF_t}{(1 + r)^t}}{I_0} \] How to use the payback period calculator Enter the initial investment as a positive amount (e.g. 100,000). The calculator treats it as an outflow at year 0. Set the discount rate (optional but recommended). Use your cost of capital or required rate of return. Fill in the yearly cash flows as net amounts (inflows minus outflows) for each year. Click “Calculate payback period” to see simple and discounted payback, NPV, PI, and the full cash flow table. Interpreting the results Simple payback : quick, intuitive measure of risk and liquidity, but ignores the time value of money and cash flows after payback. Discounted payback : more rigorous, but still ignores cash flows after the cutoff date. NPV : best single measure of value creation; a positive NPV means the project adds value at the chosen discount rate. PI : useful for ranking projects when capital is limited; PI &gt; 1 indicates value creation. FAQ What is a good payback period? It depends on your industry, risk tolerance, and capital constraints. Many companies set an internal maximum acceptable payback period (for example 3–5 years). Projects with a payback shorter than this threshold are considered, while longer proj